        'hthpCol.rd.title': 'Future R&D directions',
        'hthpCol.rd.intro': 'Section 7.2 of the IIR brief argues that stronger promotion of high-temperature heat pumps (HTHPs) depends on coordinated R&D, demonstration, and policy. The themes below are paraphrased for engineering practice—not a substitute for the official publication.',
        'hthpCol.rd.steam.title': 'Steam supply and cycle / system innovation',
        'hthpCol.rd.steam.bullets': '<ul><li>HTHPs are positioned as essential equipment to replace fossil-fuel boilers for future industrial steam supply.</li><li>Priority research: cycle and system innovations for steam generation.</li><li>Water as both working fluid and process medium deserves dedicated performance work.</li></ul>',
        'hthpCol.rd.steam.implication': '<strong>Engineering takeaway:</strong> Boiler displacement is won on steam-grade routes (R718, MVR, cascades)—design must cover steam quality, condensate recovery, and turndown together with the heat pump block.',
        'hthpCol.rd.natural.title': 'Natural working fluids and environmental regulation',
        'hthpCol.rd.natural.bullets': '<ul><li>Upcoming PFAS restrictions increase the need for natural working fluids.</li><li>Technical challenges: very high-temperature water-vapour compression; transcritical and supercritical CO₂ systems; safe use of flammable hydrocarbons.</li></ul>',
        'hthpCol.rd.natural.implication': '<strong>Engineering takeaway:</strong> Natural fluids are the compliance direction—see the <a href="./knowledge-refrigerants.html#refrigerant-data-table">common heat pump refrigerant table</a>—but high-temperature safety margins and efficiency trade-offs must be validated at system level, not on GWP alone.',
