        'hthpCol.rd.policy.implication': '<strong>Engineering takeaway:</strong> Pair technical design with eligible demos and efficiency-linked incentives—see the <a href="./heat-pump-standards.html#policies">policy map</a>. Rules vary by region; this is orientation, not legal advice.',
        'hthpCol.rd.source': 'Paraphrased from IIR Technical Brief No. 61, 2nd ed. (Apr 2026), §7.2 <em>Future R&D directions</em>. Editor’s synthesis—confirm against the official IIR publication.',
        'hthpCol.rd.sourceLink': 'IIR — High-Temperature Heat Pumps for Industrial Decarbonisation (FRIDOC)',
        'hthpCol.pain.title': 'Adoption barriers at scale',
        'hthpCol.pain.intro': 'At the <strong>2nd China High-Temperature &amp; Industrial Heat Pump Innovation Conference</strong> (Taiyuan, 15–16 May 2026), speakers including Prof. Ni Long and Prof. Wang Ruzhu—and industry presentations—highlighted barriers to promotion and scale-up beyond single-unit performance. This page focuses on <em>barriers</em>; technology <em>trends</em> from the same event are on the <a href="./briefings/conferences.html#exhibition-trends-taiyuan-hthp2026">conference notes</a>.',
        'hthpCol.pain.1.title': '1. Integration—not single equipment—is the main barrier',
        'hthpCol.pain.1.bullets': '<ul><li>Retrofits are tightly coupled to real production processes; owners fear instability or downtime.</li><li>The real gap is rarely “insufficient heat-pump COP” but lack of <strong>systems integration</strong> capability—advanced concepts stall in the field.</li><li>Many plants lack cross-cutting know-how on waste heat, electrification, and carbon tools.</li></ul>',
        'hthpCol.pain.1.implication': '<strong>For integrators &amp; owners:</strong> Lead with process risk control, measurement, and staged commissioning—not a datasheet shoot-out.',
        'hthpCol.pain.2.title': '2. Technology capability vs. market scale are misaligned',
        'hthpCol.pain.2.bullets': '<ul><li>Industrial heat demand is shifting to higher temperature bands faster than many product lines.</li><li>Domestic supply is strong in small-to-medium screw packages (~195&nbsp;°C saturated steam) but weaker on <strong>large centrifugal / turbo compression + multi-stage MVR</strong> for tens to hundreds of MW district or chemical sites—European architectures still set the reference.</li></ul>',
        'hthpCol.pain.2.implication': '<strong>For integrators &amp; owners:</strong> Match temperature band <em>and</em> duty scale in the feasibility study; do not size a 100&nbsp;MW park on a 2&nbsp;MW product narrative.',
        'hthpCol.pain.3.title': '3. Lack of process standardisation and unified norms',
        'hthpCol.pain.3.bullets': '<ul><li>The sector is still early-stage: most projects are bespoke “one deal, one design” retrofits.</li><li>Wide temperature ranges and diverse layouts make uniform product standards scarce—hard to compare bids and build trust.</li></ul>',
        'hthpCol.pain.3.implication': '<strong>For integrators &amp; owners:</strong> Publish boundary conditions, guarantees, and measurement protocols even before national standards catch up.',
        'hthpCol.pain.4.title': '4. Economics and “high unit price” anxiety',
        'hthpCol.pain.4.bullets': '<ul><li>Lifecycle economics can be favourable, but upfront capex far exceeds gas/coal boilers—an industry “high price / low volume” gap persists.</li><li>Many sites cannot meter energy properly or quantify real heat demand, so system architecture and payback look worse than they are.</li><li>Payback and value-for-money still need to improve to convince procurement.</li></ul>',
        'hthpCol.pain.4.implication': '<strong>For integrators &amp; owners:</strong> Start with heat balances and metering; bundle O&amp;M, steam quality, and carbon exposure in the business case—not equipment price alone.',
        'hthpCol.pain.5.title': '5. Upstream/downstream and platform coordination',
        'hthpCol.pain.5.bullets': '<ul><li>Structural constraints in energy supply sit alongside technology and economics.</li><li>HTHP rollout cannot rely on a single OEM—associations, supply chains, and energy-efficiency platforms must align.</li></ul>',
